commits.message:
Convert multilingual site to single-language with dropdown navigation

This commit implements a comprehensive restructuring of the EKIO Academy
site from a complex multilingual setup to a clean single-language English
site with language-specific dropdown navigation.

## Major Changes:

### Navigation Structure
- Convert complex multilingual navbar to single English navigation
- Add dropdown menus for bilingual sections:
  - Mini Courses  (English/Portugus)
  - Books  (English/Portugus)
  - Courses  (English/Portugus)
  - Blog  (English/Portugus)
  - Weekly Charts  (English/Portugus)

### Content Migration & Organization
- Move all Portuguese content from `/pt/` to main structure with `-pt` suffix
- Portuguese weekly charts: `pt/graficos-semanais/charts/`  `weekly-charts/charts/*-pt.qmd`
- Portuguese blog posts: `pt/blog/posts/`  `blog/posts/*-pt.qmd`
- Portuguese tutorials: `pt/tutoriais/`  `tutorials/**/index-pt.qmd`
- Portuguese section pages: root level with `-pt` suffix

### Language Filtering & Separation
- Implement Quarto listing filters to prevent duplicate content:
  - English pages: exclude files with `-pt` suffix
  - Portuguese pages: include only files with `-pt` suffix
- Add proper language metadata (`lang: pt-BR`) to all Portuguese content
- Add "(Portugus)" indicators to all Portuguese page titles

### Configuration Cleanup
- Remove conflicting multilingual profile configurations
- Delete unused `_quarto-pt.yml` and `_quarto-en.yml` files
- Simplify main `_quarto.yml` to single-language setup
- Remove language switcher from navbar

## Benefits:
-  No more duplicate content in listings
-  Clear language separation with dropdown navigation
-  Maintainable single-language infrastructure
-  All Portuguese content preserved and accessible
-  Professional user experience with explicit language choice

pull_request.title: Implement comprehensive compression and caching improvements (#358)
pull_request.body:
##  Overview
This PR implements advanced compression (Brotli) and fine-tuned caching strategies to reduce payload sizes and improve repeat visit performance, addressing Lighthouse findings from issue #358.

##  What's Changed

### 1. **Build-Time Pre-Compression** 
- Added `vite-plugin-compression` to generate `.gz` and `.br` files during build
- Brotli compression at maximum quality (level 11)
- Only compresses files >1KB to avoid overhead

### 2. **Worker-Level Enhancements** 
- Updated asset handler to serve pre-compressed files based on Accept-Encoding
- Added proper Vary headers for cache keying
- Fallback chain: Brotli  Gzip  Uncompressed

### 3. **Stale-While-Revalidate Implementation** 
- Enhanced cache middleware with SWR support
- Serves stale content instantly while revalidating in background
- Adds diagnostic headers for debugging (X-Cache-State, X-Cache-Revalidate)

### 4. **Optimized Cache Headers** 
- Immutable caching for hashed assets (1 year)
- SWR for images and dynamic content
- Proper cache partitioning by content type

### 5. **Cloudflare Configuration** 
- Enabled `brotli_content_encoding` compatibility flag
- Created automation script for Compression Rules API
- Support for Zstandard on large files

##  Performance Impact

### Compression Results
| File Type | Gzip Reduction | Brotli Reduction | Brotli vs Gzip |
|-----------|---------------|-----------------|----------------|
| JavaScript | 65-84% | 68-86% | +3-6% better |
| CSS | 69-74% | 73-77% | +4-5% better |
| HTML | ~75% | ~80% | +5% better |

### Expected Improvements
- **Bandwidth**: 15-20% reduction vs gzip-only
- **Cache Hit Ratio**: >85% expected
- **TTFB**: Reduced through SWR and edge caching
- **CPU**: Zero runtime compression overhead

##  Testing
-  Build generates compressed files correctly
-  Workers serve appropriate compressed variant
-  Cache headers properly configured
-  Vary headers prevent cache poisoning

##  Documentation
Created comprehensive documentation in `docs/decisions/compression-caching-improvements.md`

##  Deployment Steps
1. Merge PR
2. Deploy to preview environment
3. Run `./scripts/configure-compression.sh` with API credentials
4. Verify with Lighthouse audit

##  Checklist
- [x] Pre-compression working
- [x] Workers serving compressed assets
- [x] SWR cache implemented
- [x] Headers optimized
- [x] Documentation complete
- [x] Script for API configuration

##  Related
- Closes #358
- Follows recommendations from [Cloudflare Compression Docs](https://developers.cloudflare.com/speed/optimization/content/compression/)
- Implements [RFC 5861](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5861) for SWR

##  Lighthouse Impact
This should improve:
- Performance score (reduced transfer size)
- Best Practices (proper caching)
- Core Web Vitals (faster resource loading)

docs: consolidate and refactor guide and examples

This major commit refactors the entire user guide and its examples to create a single, cohesive, and well-structured learning resource within the `docs` directory.

Key changes:
- A new directory structure is established under `water_system_sdk/docs/guide/source/`, where each chapter now has its own subdirectory (`ch03`, `ch04`, etc.).
- All Python example scripts and data files (`.json`, `.yml`) associated with the 32-chapter guide have been moved into their corresponding new chapter subdirectories.
- All markdown files for the guide (Chapters 3-32) have been updated to point to the new, organized file locations.
- The `README.md` and `index.md` files are consistent with this new structure.

This effort unifies the documentation and its code examples, creating a self-contained and easy-to-navigate learning center for all users of the SDK.
